I tried to get out and do a little picking for the first time in awhile.

Truth be told, I'm not doing so great.

I lost my favorite human in the whole wide world a couple of months ago. I'm broken hearted. It hasn't even been a year since the passing of my other favorite human and best friend of 17 years. 

My world is already so small. Just my 3 kids and Jake and a cousin that lives out of state. They are all amazing. But all of this is so much. It's hard to raise kids, run a full time antique buisness, and animal rescue in my small world while it is falling apart around me. 

I miss my friends. Grief is hard. Life is hard.

Haven't found very many pieces of large furniture on the 127 but this piece did come back with me and is available!
#127 #primitivebench #workbench #pottingbench

do you ever drive through unfamiliar towns and think you could just apply to be a waitress at the local diner, sleep in your car for a couple of weeks, then rent a loft or apartment somewhere in town, never tell a soul, and just disappear from your life as you know it?

yeah, me neither.

My thoughts on the 127 yard sale.....

This is the 6th year I've shopped the 127. Every year I say never again, but it comes around and I check it out anyway since it is so close to home. 

As a reseller I find it isn't worth all of gas and time spent out there. Most of the roadside vendors are very high and even the local yard sales have started marking their goods up closer to a retail price point. 

Honestly, it's too much work and not a worthwhile pay off for me personally. I know a lot of others out there killing it! I just don't have the energy these days and I'm getting pickier about what I buy.

If you just love the thrill of the hunt, have plenty of time and money to spend, don't mind countless hours in the heat, driving, dodging traffic, trying to find parking, and digging through piles of dusty crusty funk....the 127 is for you!

#127yardsale

Show season is such a mixed bag. Thinking about this time last year when we set up at the worst show we've had in the 15 years of doing this. 

You just never really know when it comes to new shows. There have been some that we didn't do well at sales wise, but the show promoters went above and beyond and have been AMAZING. So we don't do those shows again but we certainly appreciate them for all of their hard work and kindness. 

Then there's shows like this one last year that was so bad for us that I just cried on the way home out of sheer frustration. The promoters seemed to only be concerned about their cliquey group of vendors and completely ignored the rest of their vendors in the other section. Which really stinks when you pay the same booth rent as everyone else. Their porters were also treated very unfairly. I don't know about yall, but I was taught to treat our service workers well.

As someone who has been both a vendor and a show promoter, these shows take INSANE amounts of work on everyone's end. 

I guess the good news is, again after 15 years of doing this, there has only been one that left a truly sour taste in my mouth. So every other show we've done has been so so good to us and we appreciate more than words can ever say!! If I have ever set up at your show (aside from the aforementioned one) just know I see you and I appreciate all of your hard work to create the show and in keeping your vendors happy!!

If you saw our stories about the vintage brass horn theft at @charmatthefarm , yes we had a theft. 

As some of you may know, I am an #autoimmunewarrior💪🏽 , I battle daily with crohns, polycystic ovary syndrome, hashimotos, and rheumatoid arthritis. I also have a blood clothing disorder and suffer from a bad leg (i had clots from below my knee running into my lungs) that has a stent and filter to help prevent clots but still has a lot of pain. Most recently I was also diagnosed with stress induced asthma (who knew that was a thing??) and I sprained my ankle (yep same one I broke last year).

Fridays set up in the rain caused some stress, which caused a flair....of everything... all at once so we left our booth a little earlier than closing (by about 15 minutes). I was in terrible pain and (for lack of a better way of putting it) because of the crohns I needed a bathroom....that wasn't a porta potty. Iykyk.

When we got back in the morning we noticed one of our brass horns was missing.

We did later find out that a "customer" decided that since we weren't there that they would just TAKE IT and supposedly pay later. 

We do not know who that customer was and we have not heard from them. It has been over 24 hours so at this point we are sticking with our initial assessment....it has been stolen.

If that supposed customer sees this and would like to make it right please message me. Otherwise you just took advantage of someone with a disease and thought that you could just steal so I stand by my original statement of shame on you.

We are once again finding ourselves overrun with cats and kittens that people continue to dump in our neighborhood.

Aside from the NINETEEN I have taken in to my house (some permanent, some fosters awaiting adoption), there are now NINE more coming to my porch to be fed and seeking shelter.

I can not take any more kitties in to the house and the latest 9 need warm shelter and food over the winter.

If you find it in your heart (and wallet) to help out, please check out Big Puddin's Wish List on Amazon. We could really use some help purchasing enough shelters for all of them.

Link in profile.

I made myself breakfast two days in a row now. It seems like such a small thing but it is actually pretty big because I made it through a full day yesterday cooking and eating gluten free & processed sugar free.

Going gluten and sugar free has been the ONLY thing that helps curb my autoimmune flare ups the last few years.

Which seems easy enough but this last year has been SO HARD on me and i got so depressed that it was hard enough to find the time and energy to cook meals for my family let alone focus on proper nourishment for myself.

I wear all the hats. I run my own business from top to bottom, rescue dozens of cats and other creatures, take care of my 3 children and do it all without much of a support network.

I grew up dirt poor in the kind of family that you run fast and far from, go full no contact, and never look back because it is the only way to escape years of neglect, abuse, and trauma.

As an adult, I found my people, my chosen family.

Two of those people, two of my most important ones, two of the best kinds of humans that have ever walked this earth died within a year of each other.

My cheerleaders, my support, my chosen family, the ones who made the hardest days bearable are not here anymore and the world is too quiet. 

But today I make my breakfast and I watch the sun rise and I focus on healing my body and my soul because I know that they would want that for me.

My office is overrun with judgemental kittens 😸

I'm exhausted, and being a caretaker/rescuer of cats feels like a full time job on top of my full time job of being caretaker of 3 kids and a house and mini farm on top of my full time job of running my own business.

Between our fosters and permanent cats we have 19 indoors and are feeding/caring for another 7 outdoors that we don't have room inside for. 

Our area is overrun with cats & kittens from heartless humans who dump animals.

If you have a little extra to give this time of year, we could definitely use the help. It is costing a small fortune for food, litter, and vet care for all of these kitties.

We have a wish list on Amazon if you can help!

After cleaning up my oatmeal with fresh cut bananas {off of the walls, the couch, the tv stand, the coffee table, AND the rug that I just cleaned last week} because one of the cats thought he could parkour off of my bowl, I am sitting here watching these maniacs knowing this is why I will never have nice things. 😆 

But honestly, I'll forgo all the nice things, I'll live with the stained rugs, the snags on the sofa, the scratched woodwork, the chipped lamps and crooked lamp shades, the hair on everything, because each and every little life that I save is FAR more important than "stuff" and having a house that looks instagram worthy. 

The only thing I really wish for is a bigger house so that I could bring more of them inside to be safe and warm.

If you see me out in public, wearing all black and dressed sloppily....just know it's because I have some serious sensory issues when it comes to clothing.

I can't wear much color, heavy fabrics, denim, leather, fleece, anything that touches my neck too much, anything even slightly constricting feeling, thick socks, anything with thick print on it......pretty much I just wear dark clothes that are lightweight stretchy fabrics.

And by sensory issues what I mean is anything else can cause an anxiety attack of pretty epic proportions. 

If you have never had to deal with sensory issues, the best way I can explain it is that it is like an itch in your brain that you can't scratch that drives you literally mad. 

But I would probably still wear all black if I didn't have sensory issues, I'd just be a lot more stylish 😆
